    <paperBody>
        <page n="01" image="pa.fr.sd.1862.01.21.01">
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>The Prospect Cheering</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"If the impatient gentlemen in warm slippers at home, insist on a movement,
                    Gen. McClellan will extemporize them into a brigade, and authorize them to make
                    a special advance towards Richmond, if it is only to give them an opportunity to
                    be tracked on the snow by their bleeding feet."</excerpt>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Relates that good news on the war front may be reported shortly. Advises
                    that it is "folly" to "clamor" for a forward movement, and emphasizes that
                    Americans must trust in the wisdom of General McClellan.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Advertisements, columns 1 and 2; poem, column 3; proceedings of Congress,
                columns 3 and 4; stories concerning flooding in California and pearls discovered in
                New Jersey, column 4; summary of the results of a meeting between representatives of
                Bards of Trade, Chambers of Commerce, and banking institutions with the Secretary of
                the Treasury, column 5; article noting the origin of "Brother Jonathan," column
            5</pageNote>
        </page>
